title: December 29, 2025 involvement between San Luis Obispo Police and DHS.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: December 29, 2025 involvement between San Luis Obispo Police and DHS.
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Requesting Memorandum of Understanding or Agreement between the San Luis Obispo Police Department and the U.S Department of Homeland Security (DHS) that authorizes assistance from the San Luis Obispo Police Department to the Department of Homeland Security or any related federal agency working thereunder, when the Department of Homeland Security or any federal agency thereunder is conducting operations within San Luis Obispo city or county. 

Also requesting assignment roster for all sworn officers on the date of 12/29/2025.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Shawn Harris

The information is also exempt from disclosure under Government Code § 7922.000 because the public interest served by not disclosing the record clearly outweighs the public interest served by disclosure of the record.

Please be advised that every effort has been made to search for all records which may fall within the scope of your records request, and, as such, we believe our search is quite thorough. However, if you have knowledge of a specific document which has not been provided in response to your request, please notify us, and we will be happy to provide the document(s) to you unless, of course, it is exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code § 7921.000 et seq.

communications.subject: RE: California Public Records Act Request: December 29, 2025 involvement between San Luis Obispo Police and DHS.
communications.communication:
Ms. Colunga-Lopez,

Thank you for providing a relevant section of the San Luis Obispo Police Department Policies and Procedures. I do not have any questions regarding this manual, I do however have a public records request related to a section of this document, to wit:

"414.6 FEDERAL REQUESTS FOR ASSISTANCE
Requests by federal immigration officials for assistance from this department should be directed
to a supervisor. The supervisor is responsible for determining whether the requested assistance
would be permitted under the California Values Act (Government Code § 7284.2 et seq.)."

Specifically,  I am requesting any document, email, or notification, in possession by the San Luis Obispo Police Department (SLOPD) received from either the US Department of Homeland Security or US Immigration and Customs Enforcement pertaining to their (ICE/DHS) activity in San Luis Obispo city and county on 12/29/2025.

Further, I am requesting any document or email from SLOPD responding to or acknowledging the aforementioned document, email, or notification from DHS/ICE  to SLOPD regarding their activity (DHS/ICE) on 12/29/2025.
 
Lastly, I am requesting the actual FEDERAL REQUEST FOR ASSISTANCE to the SLOPD from DHS or any agency thereunder related to their (DHS/ICE) activity in San Luis Obispo city and county on 12/29/2025. 

Having been surrounded by and detained (in the vernacular, "jumped") in the dark on 12/29/2025 in San Luis Obispo at 6:15am for no other reason than being impoverished and living in a rundown apartment complex with a large Hispanic population (also impoverished), by unknown masked individuals, including one one wearing a tactical vest (instead of a red coat) with a "police" patch on it without a badge (similar to another era's Gestapo or Stasi) and having not identified which agency's authority they were working under, I, as well as many of my entire state's impoverished Mexican-AMERICAN camarada, find these documents and their ability to turn our local, supine, prostrate, and compliant police departments, into nothing more than an extension of a hostile and insulated federal government located thousands of miles away (similar to England's relationship with America in its colonial past), to be of particular interest. Thank you. 

Shawn Harris

communications.subject: Records Request Response - PRR26022 Harris - Records relating to federal requests for assistance
communications.communication:
Shawn Harris,

The City of San Luis Obispo ("City") received your request pursuant to the California Public Records Act delivered via email on January 16, 2026. Today's production will complete our processing of the responsive documents and close the request.


  *   https://opengov.slocity.org/WebLink/Browse.aspx?id=220251

The document titled "Incident 251229015" includes a Summary Report and a Report Summary for an incident involving a request for assistance by DHS regarding a vehicle collision that occurred on December 29, 2025, in San Luis Obispo. SLOPD provided assistance in responding to the vehicle collision, but this assistance was not related to immigration enforcement. The document titled "12.29.25 Summary Reports" contains three Summary Reports that were created in response to DHS notifying SLOPD via phone call that DHS would be in the identified areas. These Summary Reports were created for the purpose of department awareness; SLOPD personnel did not respond to those locations or otherwise assist with DHS operations.

Please be advised that every effort has been made to search for all records which may fall within the scope of your records request, and, as such, we believe our search is quite thorough. However, if you have knowledge of a specific document which has not been provided in response to your request, please notify us, and we will be happy to provide the document(s) to you unless, of course, it is exempt from disclosure pursuant to California Government Code §7921.000 et seq.

Best,

Andrea Colunga-Lopez

Shawn Harris

communications.subject: Records Request DETERMINATION & FINAL - PRR26030 Harris - SLOPD records regarding 12/29 incident
communications.communication:
Shawn Harris,

You have requested records of the following:

  1.  Badge number of Watch Commander who participated in a call at 6:27am on 12/29/2025 regarding DHS conducting activity in the area. No Watch Commander or other officers of SLOPD participated in telephone calls with DHS on 12/29/2025. You spoke with Sgt. Brewer (badge #99297) on that date, who informed you that the department had been made aware of DHS activity in the area on that date. This information was provided by DHS to general police dispatch. Those records were provided to you on January 22, 2026 (file name "12.29.25 Summary Reports".)
  2.  Transcript or recording of the phone call involving the Watch Commander See above. No responsive records exist for this request.
  3.  Copy of report and related documents regarding vehicle collision on 12/29/25 that the Department of Homeland Security requested assistance from SLOPD (possibly at 777 Mill Street). This information was provided to you on January 22, 2026 (file name "Incident 251229015").
  4.   Any reports of stolen vehicles occurring between 12/22/2025 and 12/29/2025. This information is available online via the City's public facing crime dashboard at: https://www.slocity.org/government/department-directory/police-department/community-crime-mapping
With this response we consider your request closed.

Sara Armas

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide copy or copies of "Revised Statement of Planned Business Operation of Paige Enterprises, Inc. D/B/A Hat City Ale House" for Hat City Ale House 253 Main St, Danbury, CT in your possession in paper form. Please include document marked with "1" in the upper right hand corner. Additionally please note when each document was received by your department.

I also request that, if possible and pursuant to Conn. Gen. Stat. § 1-212(d), fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest and not made for commercial gain. The requested documents will be made available to the public at MuckRock.com.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 4 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kevin Paige

This will acknowledge receipt of your letter received on January 12, 2026,
wherein you requested information pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of
Information Act.


Please be advised that the City of Danbury is firmly committed to providing
prompt access to all records subject to disclosure under Connecticut
General Statutes §1-210, et. seq.  Accordingly, all documents will be
assembled and reviewed as quickly as reasonably possible in light of other
responsibilities and immediate commitments.  Although the City of Danbury
takes your request seriously and will respond as promptly as possible, we
reserve the right to petition the Freedom of Information Commission for a
declaratory ruling regarding requests that may be exempt from disclosure.

title: Vermont HHS response

communications.subject: Vermont Public Records Act Request: Vermont HHS response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Vermont Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Communications and correspondence with the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services regarding the Aug. 26, 2025, HHS letter requesting the Vermont Department of Health remove content from the state's Personal Responsibility Education Program curricula and program materials. For reference, the letter can be found here: https://acf.gov/sites/default/files/documents/main/08.26.25-Combined-PREP-Letters.pdf.

I also request internal communications between any Vermont Department of Health employees about the aforementioned letter. If the content changes were made, I request a copy of the material before it was changed as well as a copy of the material after it was changed.

I additionally request that, if possible, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

title: Florida Public Records Request: FACES Facial Recognition System (Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Florida Public Records Request: FACES Facial Recognition System (Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I hereby request the following records related to Okaloosa County Sheriffs Department's use of and access to the Pinellas County Sheriff's Office Face Analysis Comparison & Examination System (FACES) and related surveillance technologies:

1. FACES SYSTEM ACCESS POLICIES AND PROCEDURES:
   - All current written policies governing the department's use of the FACES facial recognition system
   - All memoranda of understanding (MOUs), memoranda of agreement (MOAs), interagency agreements, or contracts with Pinellas County Sheriff's Office or any other entity related to FACES access
   - Training materials provided to personnel authorized to use FACES
   - Standard operating procedures (SOPs) for conducting FACES searches
   - Documents describing civil rights protections, limitations on use, or oversight mechanisms for FACES searches

2. ADMINISTRATIVE LOGS AND USAGE RECORDS:
   - Organization Audit reports from FACES showing searches conducted by department personnel for the period of January 1st, 2026 to the date this request is processed if available
   - Documents sufficient to show:
     * Total number of FACES searches conducted by the department
     * User logs identifying which personnel conducted searches (names may be redacted if required by law, but please include badge numbers or employee IDs)
     * Case numbers or incident reports associated with each search
     * Stated reasons or justifications for each search
     * Any internal audit reports reviewing FACES usage for compliance or misuse

3. INTEGRATION AND RELATED TECHNOLOGIES:
   - All contracts, agreements, purchase orders, invoices, or correspondence with FUSUS/Axon or any entity related to FUSUS system implementation or integration
   - Documents describing any integration between FACES and the FUSUS platform or any other real-time surveillance systems
   - Technical specifications or system architecture documents showing how FACES connects or shares data with other surveillance technologies including but not limited to:
     * FUSUS real-time camera integration platform
     * Automated License Plate Readers (ALPRs)
     * Predictive policing systems
     * Body-worn cameras
     * ShotSpotter or other gunshot detection systems
     * Private camera registries
   - Any assessments, reports, or internal communications discussing the integration of FACES with other surveillance technologies
   - Documents describing any real-time crime center operations that utilize FACES

4. PERFORMANCE AND ACCURACY:
   - Any internal assessments, audits, or external reports evaluating the accuracy, effectiveness, or reliability of FACES
   - Documents addressing known error rates, particularly regarding demographic disparities
   - Any false positive reports or case files where FACES identification was determined to be incorrect

5. POLICY UPDATES AND OVERSIGHT:
   - Communications with Pinellas County Sheriff's Office regarding policy updates or requirements implemented in 2024
   - Documents related to any citizen oversight, internal affairs reviews, or complaints regarding FACES usage
   - Any reports provided to elected officials, oversight bodies, or the public regarding FACES usage

================================================================================

IMPORTANT CLARIFICATION REGARDING SCOPE OF REQUEST:

This request does NOT seek:
- Personally identifiable information (PII) of individuals who have been subjects of searches or investigations, including names, addresses, dates of birth, social security numbers, or biometric data of searched individuals
- Photographs, facial recognition images, or biometric templates of any individuals in the FACES database
- Specific investigative techniques, methodologies, or operational tactics that would compromise ongoing or future investigations
- Information that would reveal the identity of confidential informants or undercover officers

This request DOES seek:
- Policies, procedures, and governance documents regarding system use
- Aggregate statistical data and anonymized audit logs showing usage patterns, search volume, and compliance
- System integration information at an architectural level (what systems connect to what) without revealing specific security vulnerabilities
- Public accountability records such as oversight reports, accuracy assessments, and policy compliance reviews

I am seeking information about the governance, oversight, financial arrangements, and operational policies surrounding these technologies—not information about specific individuals, active investigations, or sensitive law enforcement techniques. All personal identifying information of subjects, victims, witnesses, or confidential sources should be redacted as required by law.

If any responsive records contain both exempt and non-exempt information, I request that you provide the non-exempt portions with appropriate redactions, as required by Florida Statutes § 119.07(1)(d).

================================================================================

FORMAT AND FEE WAIVER REQUEST:

Please provide the requested records in their original electronic, machine-readable format. For audit reports and logs, please provide data in .csv, .xlsx, or another database format if available. For policy documents, PDF format is acceptable.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. This request is made in the public interest to promote transparency and accountability regarding the use of facial recognition technology and surveillance systems. Therefore, I request a waiver of all fees associated with this request. If any fees apply, please inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request.

================================================================================

TIME FRAME:

I prefer to receive records electronically by email attachment. Florida law requires a response to this request within a reasonable time, the timeline for this request is 10 business days. If you anticipate difficulty meeting this timeline, please contact me.

If any portion of this request is denied, please:
1. Cite the specific statutory exemption being claimed for each withheld record
2. Provide a detailed explanation of why the exemption applies to the specific information being withheld
3. Indicate whether a redacted version of the record can be provided

Thank you for your assistance. Please contact me if you have any questions about this request or require clarification on any aspect of what is being sought.

Sincerely,

Kyle Searfoss

Please check that you are only including files that match the criteria specified in my initial request, rather than conducting a keyword search.

Thank you,
Rose

title: Hawaii HHS response

communications.subject: Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act Request: Hawaii HHS response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

Communications and correspondence with the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services regarding the Aug. 26, 2025, HHS letter requesting the Hawaii Department of Health remove content from the state's Personal Responsibility Education Program curricula and program materials. For reference, the letter can be found here: https://acf.gov/sites/default/files/documents/main/08.26.25-Combined-PREP-Letters.pdf.

I also request internal communications between any Hawaii Department of Health employees about the aforementioned letter. If the content changes were made, I request a copy of the material before it was changed as well as a copy of the material after it was changed.

I additionally request that, if possible, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

Thank you,
PHIG Compliance, Hearings & Investigations Specialist
Hawai'i State Department of Health | Ka 'Oihana Olakino
1250 Punchbowl Street
Honolulu, HI 96813

title: FOIA Request: Flock Safety/ALPR Systems (Pine County Sheriff (minnesota))

communications.subject: Minnesota Government Data Practices Act Request: FOIA Request: Flock Safety/ALPR Systems (Pine County Sheriff (minnesota))
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all records regarding the acquisition, installation, and use of Automated License Plate Readers (ALPRs), specifically those provided by the vendor "Flock Safety" or "Flock Group Inc." This request includes, but is not limited to:

- Right-of-Way Installation Permits: Any approved or pending permits for the installation of ALPR cameras within county right-of-ways.

- Invoices: All invoices, purchase orders, or payment records related to ALPR hardware, software, subscriptions, or services.

- Contracts: Any agreements, contracts, or Memorandums of Understanding (MOUs) entered into with ALPR vendors (specifically Flock Safety).

- Communications: All emails, memos, or correspondence discussing the installation, maintenance, or funding of ALPR systems that contain the keyword "Flock."

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Anonymous

Please confirm receipt of the 42 files attached.
Thank you.

title: Wounded Warrior Caregivers Credit Tax Statistics

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: Wounded Warrior Caregivers Credit Tax Statistics
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Information related to the Wounded Warrior Caregivers Credit from as far back as data systems will allow through 2025. Specifically, the following information, as it is available:

1) Number of returns that claimed the credit
2) Total amount of credits claimed ($)
3) If available, (1) and (2) separately by taxpayer characteristics, such as filing status, marital status, age of taxpayer, AGI range, number of dependents, etc.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Gabrielle Pepin

City of Berkeley ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #25-1326: This is in response to your June 9, 2025 Public Records Act request for: [To Whom It May Concern: Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: All Property Inventory Forms created on June 4th-June 6th 2025. All photographs of discarded and stored property taken on June 4th 2025 by City Staff around Eighth and Harrison Street. All emails communications by Peter Radu, sent or received, regarding homeless encampments, between May 20th 2025 and June 9th 2025 The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. ...] The City has identified documents which are responsive to your request. A partial production of those records is attached to this letter. Certain documents and portions of documents have been withheld based upon the deliberative process privilege. (Cal. Gov. Code §§ 7922.000& 7927.705 (formerly Gov. Code §§ 6254(a) & 6255)). Certain records have been withheld based upon the attorney-client privilege. (Cal. Gov. Code § 7927.705 (formerly § 6254(k))). Certain records have been withheld based upon the official information privilege because the need for confidentiality of the information outweighs the necessity of disclosure in the interest of justice. (Cal. Evid. Code § 1040.) The City is in the process of compiling and reviewing additional documents and anticipates being able to produce additional responsive documents by October 28th, 2025. If you have any questions concerning your request, please feel free to contact me at kperez@berkeleyca.gov ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Berkeley.

title: Dataset: 911 Call Data (E-911 Communications Division)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Dataset: 911 Call Data (E-911 Communications Division)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

RAW Computer Aided Dispatch Data queried out of your emergency phone system on 911 calls for service from January 2014 to the most recent date data is collected. In CSV, TXT, or XML format, a machine-readable spreadsheet (not XLSX format). 

Here are the column headers which I am requesting:

Master Incident Number or Event Number – Unique numerical identifier of the call for service
Case Number – If an incident report was written, this is the file number, which can be joined to the incidents and arrests datasets
Call Date – Date the call for service was generated
Call Time – Time the call for service was generated
Source – How the call was generated from the public, or self-initiated by an officer
Priority – The priority level of the call response, with ‘P’ being the highest, followed in order numerically
Nature – The description of the call for service.
Address – The block number and street or intersection of the call for service.
Latitude/longitude - coordinates for call of service
X – Mapping coordinate of the call for service
Y – Mapping coordinate of the call for service
District – The patrol district where the call for service was located.
Beat – The patrol beat where the call for service was located, which is a sub-division of the district
Tract – The census tract where the incident occurred, based on 2010 census data
Disposition – How the call for service was closed
Cancelled – Whether the call for service was cancelled prior to officer arrival
Dispatch Date and Time - The exact date and time when the dispatcher sent the call to emergency responders, such as police, fire, or EMS
Entry Date and Time - The date and time when the call was initially logged into the 911 computer-aided dispatch (CAD) system
Received Date and Time - The date and time when the 911 call was first answered by the dispatch center
Enroute Date and Time - The date and time when the assigned responder (e.g., a patrol car, ambulance, or fire truck) began traveling to the incident location
On Scene Date and Time - The date and time when the responder arrived at the scene of the incident
Close Date and Time - The date and time when the incident or call was marked as completed or resolved in the CAD system
Dispatcher ID - A unique identifier for the dispatcher who handled and managed the 911 call. This may be used for tracking or auditing purposes

If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Filed Requests

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request #77593
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Upon review, additional data fields are necessary to fully interpret the records already requested and/or produced. I therefore request the following additional column headers, to the extent they exist in your CAD system, for the same date range (January 2014 to the most recent date data is collected), in CSV, TXT, or XML format:

* Unique Identifier – A unique numerical identifier for each call for service, if distinct from the master incident or event number
* Dispatcher ID(s) – Identifier(s) for all dispatchers who handled the call, if multiple
* Responder ID – A unique identifier for the responding unit(s) or team(s)
* Prime Unit – Identifier indicating the primary response unit
* Other Units – All additional responding unit identifiers
* Back-up Requested – Indicator or code showing whether back-up was requested
* Transport – Indicator (Y/N) of whether transport occurred
* Transport Start and End Times – If transport occurred
* Transport Destination Address – The address or facility to which transport occurred
* Program or Response Type – Any field identifying non-police, co-response, or alternative response teams (including behavioral health, crisis, or care-based units), if applicable

If any of the above fields are stored under different names, codes, or tables, I request the functional equivalent fields.

I also request any available data dictionary or codebook necessary to interpret these fields.

If you deny any portion of this supplemental request, please cite the specific statutory exemption relied upon and provide the applicable appeal procedures as required by law.

As before, these records are requested for non-commercial purposes and will be made available to the general public. Please inform me in advance of any fees associated with fulfilling this request.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Sincerely,
FR

communications.subject: Acknowledgement MPIA 25-1346
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Deborah Levi:

This is an acknowledgement of your request for public information submitted to the Document Compliance Unit (“DCU”) of the Baltimore Police Department (“BPD”). Your request is governed by the Maryland Public Information Act (“PIA”), Maryland Code, General Provisions Article (“GP”), Sections 4-101 et seq. DCU will attempt to process your request promptly. However, our response may take longer than ten (10) working days, the reasons for which may include the scope of your request, the type and volume of potentially responsive records, and the nature of the search, review, and preparation that is required. DCU will contact you with the availability of records and the possible costs associated with this request, as soon as the information is made available by the Custodian of Records. Likewise, if the DCU and/or the Custodian of Records need you to clarify your request, DCU will than contact.
Your request seeks Public Integrity Bureau’s (PIB) administrative disciplinary records recently made disclosable pursuant to Anton’s Law, S.B. 178 (2021 Session). Although we have not yet investigated the scope of your particular request, production of these records often involves expenditure of substantial resources in the search for, preparation of, and reproduction of responsive materials.
BPD will offer requestors of such records the option to receive the disciplinary history summary for each BPD member identified in the request in lieu of a comprehensive response to the request. These summaries provide an overview of all disciplinary investigations against the subject officer including the disposition of each, can be prepared more quickly than a full disciplinary file, and can be produced at little or no cost to the requestor. The summary may provide all of the information you seek, or may enable you to resubmit a more tailored request, thereby reducing the fee BPD charges to recover its costs in producing the materials you require.
Please respond to this email within 10 business days indicating whether you wish to receive disciplinary history summaries in lieu of your request as originally stated. This information is required for DCU to move forward with either 1) preparing an estimate of the cost associated with the production of the disciplinary history summary or 2) preparing an estimate of the costs associated with the production of records responsive to the full scope of your request. No further action will be taken by DCU until we receive your response. Please refer to tracking # MPIA 25-1346 in any subsequent correspondence pertaining to this matter. All follow up correspondence should be made in writing and submitted to the DCU’s e-mail: DCU@baltimorepolice.org<mailto:DCU@baltimorepolice.org>.


P/O Rico Calcitrai
Baltimore Police Department
Document Compliance Unit
Legal Affairs Division
242 W. 29th Street
Baltimore Maryland, 21211
DCU@baltimorepolice.org<mailto:DCU@baltimorepolice.org>
MPIA request forms
http://law.baltimorecity.gov/office-legal-affairs-baltimore-police-department

If you are not the intended recipient, or the employee or agent responsible for delivering the message to the intended recipient, you are notified that any distribution or copying of this communication is strictly prohibited. The materials in this e-mail are private and may contain sensitive law enforcement information. Please note that e-mail is not necessarily confidential or secure. title: Banned books list (North Carolina Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Banned books list (North Carolina Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A list of all books and other printed publications that are banned or otherwise not permitted in prisons. Please include the title and author of the publication. If available, please include the reasons for prohibiting the publication, as well as the date of the decision.

If possible, please send this information in a searchable spreadsheet format, such as an Excel file or a CSV file.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

title: Police disciplinary files (Stevens County Prosecuting Attorney)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Police disciplinary files (Stevens County Prosecuting Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aspen Ford

title: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Muskingum County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Muskingum County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Use of force (UOF) data dating from January 1, 2017 to December 31, 2025. If possible, please provide this data in database or spreadsheet format and include the case number, incident date, incident time, subject injured indicator, subject injury force related info (e.g. Yes or No), subject age, subject gender, subject ethnicity, subject weapon type, incident area occurred, force type, officer division (e.g. law enforcement operations, detention/correctional operations, etc.), badge number and names associated with the officers involved. If one or more of these fields or dates is unavailable, provide all fields and/or information that is available responsive to my request. If no database or spreadsheet format is available, please provide copies of each individual use of force report or other report where use of force information is documented/reported by officers. Note, this is for all use of force incidents reported by your agency, not limited to only those incidents required to be reported under state or federal programs.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

--- City of Redmond --- 
 RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of 1/2/2026, Reference # W035473-010226 Dear Rose  Terse, The Redmond Police Records Division received your public records request on 1/2/2026 for “To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 

Mission documentation of each UAS deployment in 2025, sufficient to determine the date, time, location, and purpose of each deployment. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Rose Terse 

Upload documents directly: https://www.muckrock.com/respond/2169972/” 
The Records Division has reviewed all databases and has located records responsive to your request.  Please log into your account on the Police Records Portal to retrieve these records. If you do not have a password, you can request one from the login page (your account is tied to the email address receiving this message). 
This request is now closed. If you have any follow-up questions regarding the closing of this request, please promptly contact us by responding to this message.  If you would like a review of your request, the process can be found in Section 10 of Redmond’s Public Records Disclosure Rules of Procedure. If you are seeking further records not covered in this request, please submit a new request through our  portal.  This request is closed and the City is no longer fulfilling it. Per state law (RCW 42.56.550), the Public Records Act’s one-year statute of limitations starts on this date. The statute of limitations defines the maximum time limit to file a lawsuit if you determine your records request was not fulfilled appropriately. 
Cordially, 
Police Public Disclosure Desk Redmond Police Department Police Records Portal

title: Drone as First Responder program contract and details (Campbell Police Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Drone as First Responder program contract and details (Campbell Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. A copy of all Requests for Proposal (or equivalent solicitations) and vendor bids and supplemental materials associated with this agency’s procurement of devices and services related to the establishment and execution of a Drone-as-First-Responder (DFR) program

2. A copy of this agency’s  contract (as well as all amendments, attachments, and exhibits) for devices and services used in its DFR program

3. Copies of all policies, directives, guidelines, and procedures governing this agency’s use of drones and the execution of operations under its DFR program, including documentation describing the device models and technical specifications of the devices used and any policies regarding the “curtilage” of a person’s property

4. A copy of all data sharing agreements and lists of other entities with which this agency shares or receives information. This includes the list of all agencies that receive notifications based on this agency’s list of license plates and vehicles of interest (often referred to as a “hot list”) and the list of all agencies that have access to all vehicle scans conducted by this agency’s devices

5. A copy of all manuals and operational references for this agency’s use of drones and the implementation and use of the DFR program. This includes all policies, procedures, and manuals related to the following elements of the execution of the drone and DFR program: 
a. appropriate deployment and use of the drone or drones; 
b. collection of camera footage, audio, and other data;
c. retention of footage, audio, and other data;
d. sharing of footage, audio, and other data, including via third-party networks and across jurisdictions; 
e. appropriate positioning of drone cameras and other payloads during flights;
f. the appropriate protection of collected, stored, and shared audio, footage, and other data
g. the policies and mechanisms used for auditing drone and DFR use, including appropriate investigatory use and access
h. the policies and mechanisms of consequences of unauthorized and inappropriate access to the drone or DFR systems

6. All materials sufficient to show the complete list of features and integration capabilities associated with the drone or DFR programs, including all materials related to device or DFR program integration with automated license plate readers (ALPRs), gunshot detection, video analytics, AI-enabled analysis, and other datasets, surveillance tools, and analytical systems.

7. All communications between a representative of this agency and a representative of the private entity from which this agency has procured DFR program devices and services for the period from January 1, 2025 through the current date.

8. A copy of the drone flight log for the period from January 1, 2025 through today, including the date and time of the flight, the investigatory purpose of the flight, the drone operator, and any other segregable information

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Riley Overstreet

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
RE: Police Records Request of September 23, 2025, Reference # P000901-092325 Dear Riley Overstreet, This email is in response to your email dated September 23, 2025, which was received by the City on the same day. Except as expressly noted below, it is the City’s intent to cooperate with you in identifying any records that would be responsive to your request, and to expeditiously provide you with those records. 

However, as you may be aware, under California Law, a request for documents must reasonably describe an identifiable record, and must be focused and specific. (See Cal. Govt. Code § 7922.530(a); Rogers v. Superior Court, 19 Cal.App.4th 469, 481.) Likewise, cities are not required to create a new record in response to a request. (See Haynie v. Superior Court, 26 Cal.4th 1061, 1075.) Nevertheless, the City will use its best efforts to identify all records that may be responsive to your requests. 

Due to the time required to search, compile, and review potentially responsive documents, I am requesting an additional 14 days from the date of this response to complete the process. If further time is needed, I will notify you accordingly. As of now, the anticipated response date is October 13, 2025. For questions or additional information, please reply to this email. Sincerely, Mihui Cho

title: Police Information Sharing Policies with Immigration Authorities

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Police Information Sharing Policies with Immigration Authorities
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records: 

1. All departmental or municipal policies regarding communication and information sharing between departmental officers or employees and federal agents/agencies within the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) or the U.S. Department of Homeland Security (DHS), including but not limited to the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE). The records request includes, but is not limited to, policies regarding: 

A. Fingerprint and other data sharing, 

B. ICE detainer requests,   

C. Compliance with federal immigration enforcement efforts, including guidance or policies around when communication with ICE officers is allowed, and 

D. Communicating with federal immigration enforcement officers. 

This request covers any policies that are currently in effect or that have been in effect at any point on or after January 20, 2025. 

2. The three most recent communications (e.g., emails, text messages, call logs or transcripts, or otherwise) between a departmental officer or employee and a federal DHS or ICE employee. In addition, I request all records related to these communications, including, but not limited to, any records indicating that the department was made aware of the communications, discussions of their content or implications, evaluations them for compliance with departmental or other city policies, identification or acknowledgement of any potential policy violations, and any internal responses, disciplinary actions, or follow-up measures resulting from these communications. 

3. All records relating to incidents, if any, from January 20, 2025, to the day this request is responded to, in which an individual was taken from the department’s custody directly into ICE custody. For each incident, the records request includes, but is not limited to, booking and transfer records, communications with ICE or other federal agencies, internal documentation or discussion of the transfer, and internal notes, memos, or documentation referencing communication with DHS or ICE.

For each request, I am not seeking identifying information, and I will accept anonymized or redacted data as necessary to protect identities. 

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest. I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Joshua Dankoff 

Joshuadankoff@cfjj.org  

Director of Strategic Initiatives 

Citizens for Juvenile Justice  

(submitted via MuckRock platform)

title: OMI Otero Death Autopsy

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: OMI Otero Death Autopsy
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records relating to any autopsy, review, or consultation performed by OMI on Jhon Javier Benavides Quintana, who died at the Otero County Processing Center on June 15, 2024. See https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ecuadoran-national-passes-away-ice-custody. 

Thank you in advance for your response to this IPRA request! 

Andrew Free

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

title: Fusus audit logs

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Fusus audit logs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Audit logs/audit trails documenting each time a department account has conducted a vehicle/person search or accessed live or recorded video footage through the Fusus platforms from 11/1/2025 until the date this request is processed.

This data should be stored in a database and so I ask that you provide it to me as a  .csv, .xls, or other database filetype.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

title: Joplin's CJIS Documents

communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: Joplin's CJIS Documents
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Information Exchange Agreements maintained by the Joplin Police Department.  These would be agreements signed by agencies JPD enters into relationships with for sharing, managing, or providing CJIS data in some way.  This would detail things like: breach handling and notification, security obligations of both parties, approved methods of sharing, and so on.

Incident Response Plans maintained by the City of Joplin or the Joplin Police Department in regards to CJIS.  This would be the plan to identify, contain, eradicate, and recover from a CJIS incident.

The acceptable use policy for mobile devices used by employees of Joplin's Police Department.  This would cover devices that are not on-premise, but still have access to CJI systems such as tablets, smartphones, laptops, and so on.  This policy should cover devices owned by the city and devices owned by employees separately.

Any access agreement signed by employees or vendors before attaining access to CJI systems.

Any configuration record indicating whether Multifactor Authentication is enabled on Flock systems. This record is requested in screenshot form for ease of production by the recipient.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Michael

 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C243130-101525. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button.

  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment.

Ann Vuong

title: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Scioto County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Scioto County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Use of force (UOF) data dating from January 1, 2017 to December 31, 2025. If possible, please provide this data in database or spreadsheet format and include the case number, incident date, incident time, subject injured indicator, subject injury force related info (e.g. Yes or No), subject age, subject gender, subject ethnicity, subject weapon type, incident area occurred, force type, officer division (e.g. law enforcement operations, detention/correctional operations, etc.), badge number and names associated with the officers involved. If one or more of these fields or dates is unavailable, provide all fields and/or information that is available responsive to my request. If no database or spreadsheet format is available, please provide copies of each individual use of force report or other report where use of force information is documented/reported by officers. Note, this is for all use of force incidents reported by your agency, not limited to only those incidents required to be reported under state or federal programs.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

title: Chemical and Biological Weapon Incidents within the United States

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chemical and Biological Weapon Incidents within the United States
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting all documents related to military personnel carrying out missions, responses, or other incidents involving chemical or biological weapons, substances, munitions, or agents within the United States of America, including all states and territories,  between January 1, 2005 and August 14, 2025. This includes incident requests from EODIMS on incidents involving such weapons or agents. 

I request that I be properly classified as a news media requester. I am an investigative researcher for Bellingcat, and I am requesting this information in that capacity and request that fees be waived for this request.

I am requesting expedited processing as I am a ”person primarily engaged in disseminating information” and there is urgency to inform the public about the activities of US military personnel, especially as it pertains to incidents involving chemical and biological agents that occur within the United States. 

Bellingcat is widely recognized for its reporting, and publishing regular features on issues of public interest and importance using open source material. 

If you have any questions about my media status, please contact me.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Trevor Ball

title: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Use of force (UOF) data dating from January 1, 2017 to December 31, 2025. If possible, please provide this data in database or spreadsheet format and include the case number, incident date, incident time, subject injured indicator, subject injury force related info (e.g. Yes or No), subject age, subject gender, subject ethnicity, subject weapon type, incident area occurred, force type, officer division (e.g. law enforcement operations, detention/correctional operations, etc.), badge number and names associated with the officers involved. If one or more of these fields or dates is unavailable, provide all fields and/or information that is available responsive to my request. If no database or spreadsheet format is available, please provide copies of each individual use of force report or other report where use of force information is documented/reported by officers. Note, this is for all use of force incidents reported by your agency, not limited to only those incidents required to be reported under state or federal programs.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

title: Florida Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety audit (Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Florida Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety audit (Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to Florida's Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I submit the following records request:

I would first and foremost like to thank your department for previous cooperation with my audit requests as I know that this requires additional time and effort from department personnel. However, my previous audit left some questions as to the department's use of Flock systems and safeguards that are in place to ensure the security and privacy of the residents of Okaloosa County. My intent is to gain insight into your department's use of the Flock system due to national concern of agencies overstepping 4th amendment rights and well documented misuse of this system by other agencies. If your department is truly using this system as advertised, then I would love nothing more than to share those facts with concrete evidence as I imagine that this information would help citizens, including myself, to feel more at ease with the use of this system around our homes and places of work. 

- Records Related to the Department's Flock Safety System:

1. Financial Records:
   1a. Any internal financial audits conducted regarding expenditures on the Flock Safety contract from inception to present
   1b. If no formal internal audit exists, a written statement or documentation showing the approximate annual expenditure by the department on the Flock Safety contract
   1c. The total contract value
   1d. The contract renewal date or expiration date
   1e. Any amendments to the original contract affecting financial terms

2. Contract and Agreement Documents:
   2a. The complete, executed contract(s) between the Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department and Flock Safety, including all terms and conditions
   2b. Service level agreements
   2c. Data sharing provisions and agreements with Flock Safety
   2d. Privacy disclosure information and policies
   2e. Data retention and deletion policies
   2f. Third-party data access provisions
   2g. All amendments, addendums, or modifications to the original contract

3. Internal Use Policy and Accountability Measures:
   3a. Policies regarding authorized users and permissible uses of the system
   3b. Training requirements for deputies and other personnel
   3c. Audit and oversight procedures
   3d. Accountability measures for system misuse or unauthorized access
   3e. Procedures for conducting searches and queries
   3f. Legal justification requirements for searches (warrant requirements, reasonable suspicion standards, etc.)

4. Security and Privacy Safeguards:
   4a. Authentication requirements (e.g., two-factor authentication policies)
   4b. Password policies, including requirements for length, complexity, and rotation
   4c. Standards for regular user account access audits and reviews
   4d. Cybersecurity vulnerability assessments or security reviews conducted on the Flock Safety system

- Clarification Regarding Requested Records:

To be clear, I am requesting financial documents, contract documents, policy documents, and security documentation (of the administrative use of the Flock System) that document expenditures, contractual obligations, internal governance, and system security measures. The contracts, financial records, and policy documents requested are standard public records that document how public funds are spent and how government agencies operate, and do not contain information that would compromise law enforcement operations, ongoing investigations, or reveal investigative practices as these documents are administrative in nature.

- Accommodation for Partial Exemptions:

If any portion of the requested records contains information that your department believes is exempt under Florida law, I respectfully request that you provide the records with appropriate redactions of only that specific exempt information, rather than withholding the records in their entirety. Florida's Public Records Law requires that exemptions be narrowly construed, and non-exempt portions of records must be disclosed even when some portions are exempt.

- Additional Questions:

Here are several questions that I would greatly appreciate responses to in addition to the above requested records:

1. Is your department aware of the numerous security vulnerabilities that have been discovered by security researchers (such as the YouTube channel Benn Jordan: see this video; https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uB0gr7Fh6lY) to include antiquated operating system software, admin portals left open to web access with default credentials, and Flock accounts for sale on the dark web to name a few?

2. I saw on your departments Facebook post, on the 12th of January 2026, that your department requires outside agencies to provide warrants and/or investigative reasoning for data regarding Okaloosa residents. In my audit of your logs I noticed several logs that indicated that searches were also being done on behalf of county investigators as well (specifically A. Planck). Are internal uses of the system for investigations into suspicious activities or on behalf of investigators also required to provide a warrant or other legal justification for searches conducted on the Flock system?

3. What is your department's view on the case currently under review of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia regarding Flock cameras? To quote an article: "Chief Judge Davis rejected the city’s motion to dismiss the lawsuit, citing the United States Supreme Court case Carpenter v. United States, which held that using cell phone location data to track someone’s movements is a search that requires a warrant under the Fourth Amendment. Chief Judge Davis wrote, “a reasonable person could believe that society’s expectations, as laid out by the Court in Carpenter, are being violated by the Norfolk Flock system.”".
(citation: https://ij.org/press-release/judge-rules-lawsuit-challenging-norfolks-use-of-flock-cameras-can-proceed/)

- Format and Delivery:

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine-readable format. For example, please provide PDF format for contracts and policy documents, and spreadsheet files where applicable for financial data. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment or Dropbox link.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as Florida law requires. If you believe any portion of the requested records is exempt, please provide a detailed explanation identifying the specific exemption and how it applies to the specific data withheld.

Sincerely,


Kyle Searfoss

title: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Cumberland County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: Sheriff use of force data (2017-2025) (Cumberland County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maine Freedom of Access Act, I hereby request the following records:

Use of force (UOF) data dating from January 1, 2017 to December 31, 2025. If possible, please provide this data in database or spreadsheet format and include the case number, incident date, incident time, subject injured indicator, subject injury force related info (e.g. Yes or No), subject age, subject gender, subject ethnicity, subject weapon type, incident area occurred, force type, officer division (e.g. law enforcement operations, detention/correctional operations, etc.), badge number and names associated with the officers involved. If one or more of these fields or dates is unavailable, provide all fields and/or information that is available responsive to my request. If no database or spreadsheet format is available, please provide copies of each individual use of force report or other report where use of force information is documented/reported by officers. Note, this is for all use of force incidents reported by your agency, not limited to only those incidents required to be reported under state or federal programs.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by 1 M.R.S.A. § 408(6). The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

title: GRANDVIEW SCHOOL DISTRICT – Salary and Compensation Records of District Public Records Officer 01-01-2020 to 10-01-2024

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: GRANDVIEW SCHOOL DISTRICT – Salary and Compensation Records of District Public Records Officer 01-01-2020 to 10-01-2024
communications.communication:
10-01-2024

Via email: compliance@gsd200.org

Grandview SCHOOL DISTRICT – Salary and Compensation Records of District Public Records Officer 01-01-2020 to 10-01-2024

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

1. Any/all records and writings regarding salary, benefits, and compensation of the Grandview School District Public Records Officer.

2. Any/all records and writings regarding salary, benefits, and compensation of any individual performing Public Records Request functions on behalf of the Grandview School District.

3. Any/all records and writings referencing any software packages used in the search for and processing of Public Records Requests by the Grandview School District.

4. Any/all records and writings referencing any invoices for any legal work (including consulting and representation) performed on behalf of the Grandview School District in response to public records requests and/or public records act litigation. 

DATE RANGE OF REQUEST

The date range for records responsive to this request is January 01, 2020 - October 01, 2024.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS - ORDER OF PRODUCTION

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in REVERSE CHRONOLOGICAL FORMAT BY DATE. The most recent public records should be produced first and the oldest records produced last by date.

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION PROCESSING AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

Washington State Law is clear that the use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA) for a public records request is optional for the requestor. Respectfully I decline. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment to this email address.

Please do not register this requestor for, nor direct this requestor to the use of any 3rd party commercial portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other online service other than a direct NO PASSWORD REQUIRED, NO REGISTRATION REQUIRED, internet cloud-based download link, or electronic email.

Do not send any portion of this public records request to any 3rd party for-profit corporation such as GOVQA, a Grannicus Corporation or NEXT-REQUEST.

Do not register this request with any for profit portal or 3rd party organization such as GOVQA, a Grannicus Corporation, or NEXT-REQUEST.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide copies of all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format. Please provide all electronic records in the fewest number of individual files as per native format or use free .zip compression in each installment.

FEES

In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION LOGS

Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION

The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

PRESERVATION OF PUBLIC RECORDS *** ANTICIPATE LITIGATION ***

WAC 44-14-03005 RETENTION OF PUBLIC RECORDS

The lawful destruction of public records is governed by retention schedules. The unlawful destruction of public records can be a crime. RCW 40.16.010 and 40.16.020. An agency is prohibited from destroying a public record, even if it is about to be lawfully destroyed under a retention schedule, if a public records request has been made for that record. RCW 42.56.100. Additional retention requirements might apply if the records may be relevant to actual or anticipated litigation. The agency is required to retain the record until the record request has been resolved.

Note: An agency can be found to violate the Public Records Act and be subject to the attorneys' fees and penalty provision if it prematurely destroys a requested record after a request is made. See Yacobellis v. City of Bellingham, 55 Wn. App. 706, 780 P.2d 272 (1989). However, it is not a violation of the Public Records Act if a record is destroyed prior to an agency's receipt of a public records request for that record. Bldg. Indus. Ass'n of Wash. v. McCarthy, 152 Wn. App. 720, 218 P.3d 196 (2009); West v. Dep't of
Nat. Res., 163 Wn. App. 238, 258 P.3d 78 (2011). The Public Records Act (chapter 42.56 RCW) and the records retention statutes (chapter 40.14 RCW) are two different laws.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email reply.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.
